<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,463,2037]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,572,597]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Description</emphasis>
. Vase-shaped sponge, 150 × 180 × 
<quantity box="[741,821,572,596]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="40.0">40 mm</quantity>
in diameter (
<figureCitation box="[972,1063,572,597]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1978,2000]" captionTargetBox="[201,1389,185,1953]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[201,1389,185,1953]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 5. Spheciospongia excentrica (Burton, 1931). A-D. In situ; E &amp; F. Skeletal architecture (E, x5; F, x10); G. Tylostyles of two classes." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2651458/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 5A</figureCitation>
). Surface smooth with oscules, 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
in diameter, scattered randomly on the inner side of the vase. Texture tough, firm and rubbery to the touch, barely compressible. Lip area of vase, thick with vein-like appearance. Surface membrane visible in preserved specimen. Colour in life dirty yellow with dark brown interior; in preservative, exterior grey, interior dark grey to brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,463,2037]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,302,751,776]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Skeleton</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[316,381,751,776]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1978,2000]" captionTargetBox="[201,1389,185,1953]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[201,1389,185,1953]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 5. Spheciospongia excentrica (Burton, 1931). A-D. In situ; E &amp; F. Skeletal architecture (E, x5; F, x10); G. Tylostyles of two classes." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2651458/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
B–D). Choanosomal skeleton consists of a dense, irregular reticulation of bundles of tylostyles and styles. Spirasters scattered randomly throughout the choanosome. Subdermal cavities present filled with sand and lined with a confused reticulation of tylostyles. The ectosomal skeleton is composed of a dense, confused paratangential reticulation of tylostyles and a few spirasters. Tylostyles occasionally protrude through the ectosome.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,463,2037]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,460,932,957]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Spicules. Megascleres</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[477,596,932,957]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1978,2000]" captionTargetBox="[201,1389,185,1953]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[201,1389,185,1953]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 5. Spheciospongia excentrica (Burton, 1931). A-D. In situ; E &amp; F. Skeletal architecture (E, x5; F, x10); G. Tylostyles of two classes." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2651458/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 5E, F</figureCitation>
).Tylostyles, smooth, slightly sinuous with variable proximal head shape, distal end hastate to fusiform: 428 (398–499) × 6 (6) µm, n = 10. Styles, smooth, slightly sinuous with distal end fusiform: 388 (326–432) × 7 (7) µm, n = 10. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[655,806,1004,1029]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Microscleres</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[821,911,1004,1029]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1978,2000]" captionTargetBox="[201,1389,185,1953]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[201,1389,185,1953]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 5. Spheciospongia excentrica (Burton, 1931). A-D. In situ; E &amp; F. Skeletal architecture (E, x5; F, x10); G. Tylostyles of two classes." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2651458/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 5G</figureCitation>
). Spirasters, C-shaped with spines on the outer curve: 18 (17–19) µm, n = 10.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,463,2037]" box="[199,1435,1076,1101]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,652,1076,1101]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Substratum, depth range and ecology.</emphasis>
The sponge is found on exposed rocky/sandy area at a depth of 
<specimenCount box="[1371,1435,1076,1100]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="generic">
<quantity box="[1371,1431,1076,1100]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="m" value="18.0">18 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,463,2037]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,1111,1136]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Etymology</emphasis>
. Named in honour of David 
<collectingRegion box="[653,723,1111,1136]" country="Bermuda" name="Smith's" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Smith</collectingRegion>
, who rescued the author TS’s son from drowning while he was out collecting sponges in Sodwana Bay. Ndabazithe is David’s Zulu name which means ‘respect’.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,463,2037]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1183,1208]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Remarks.</emphasis>
This sponge has a skeletal arrangement typical of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Marshall" authorityYear="1892" box="[994,1171,1183,1208]" class="Demospongiae" family="Clionaidae" genus="Spheciospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[994,1171,1183,1208]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Spheciospongia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and its surface is lined with pore sieves. The spicules are clearly those of the family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="d'Orbigny" authorityYear="1851" box="[832,957,1220,1245]" class="Demospongiae" family="Clionaidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Porifera" rank="family">Clionaidae</taxonomicName>
. The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Marshall" authorityYear="1892" box="[1088,1266,1220,1245]" class="Demospongiae" family="Clionaidae" genus="Spheciospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1088,1266,1220,1245]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Spheciospongia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is well defined (
<bibRefCitation author="Rutzler" box="[158,309,1255,1280]" firstAuthor="Rutzler" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="173 - 185" refId="ref48524" refString="Rutzler, K. (2002) Family Clionaidae D'Orbigny, 1851. In: Hooper, J. N. A. &amp; Van Soest, R. W. M. (Eds.), Systema Porifera. A guide to the classification of sponges. Fol. 1. Kluwer Academic / Plenum Publishers, New York, Boston, Dordrecht, London and Moscow, pp. 173 - 185. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 1 - 4615 - 0747 - 5 _ 19" type="book chapter" year="2002">Rützler 2002</bibRefCitation>
) with currently seven species described from the WIO [(
<taxonomicName authority="(Ridley 1884)" authorityName="Ridley" authorityYear="1884" baseAuthorityName="Ridley" baseAuthorityYear="1884" box="[956,1277,1255,1280]" class="Demospongiae" family="Clionaidae" genus="Spheciospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="vagabunda">
<emphasis box="[956,1109,1255,1280]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">S. vagabunda</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Ridley" box="[1125,1270,1255,1280]" firstAuthor="Ridley" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="366 - 482" refId="ref48144" refString="Ridley, S. O. (1884) Spongiida. In: Report on the Zoological Collections made in the Indo-Pacific Ocean during the Voyage of H. M. S. Alert 1881 - 2. British Museum (Natural History), London. Istituti Biologici della Universita di Genova, 58 - 59, 69 - 75, pp. 366 - 482 + 582 - 635." type="journal article" year="1884">Ridley 1884</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Burton 1931)" authorityName="Burton" authorityYear="1931" baseAuthorityName="Burton" baseAuthorityYear="1931" class="Demospongiae" family="Clionaidae" genus="Spheciospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="excentrica">
<emphasis box="[1290,1436,1256,1280]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">S. excentrica</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Burton" box="[158,312,1292,1316]" firstAuthor="Burton" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="337 - 358" refId="ref41703" refString="Burton, M. (1931) On a collection of marine sponges mostly from the Natal coast. Annals of the Natal Museum, 6 (3), 337 - 358." type="journal article" year="1931">Burton 1931</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lendenfeld 1897)" authorityName="Lendenfeld" authorityYear="1897" baseAuthorityName="Lendenfeld" baseAuthorityYear="1897" box="[340,686,1292,1317]" class="Demospongiae" family="Clionaidae" genus="Spheciospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="florida">
<emphasis box="[340,452,1292,1317]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">S. florida</emphasis>
(
